## {{ rule.title }}

The [§ 199A](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section199A&num=0&edition=prelim) Qualified Business Income (QBI) deduction can shelter up to 20 % of qualified business income — but it does **not** apply to this return, and the engine grants **zero** § 199A deduction.

{% set gate = rule.outputs[0].value | from_json -%}
{% if gate.business_income_source == "foreign" -%}
[§ 199A(c)(3)(A)(i)](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section199A&num=0&edition=prelim) defines a "qualified item of income" as one **effectively connected with the conduct of a trade or business within the United States** (cross-referencing [§ 864(c)](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section864&num=0&edition=prelim)). A U.S. citizen resident in Germany earning German-source freelance income is conducting that business **within Germany, not within the United States**. The income is therefore **not** effectively connected with a U.S. trade or business, it is **not** QBI, and **no § 199A deduction is allowed** on it.

Accordingly the § 199A status here is **{{ gate.status }}**: the deduction is **{{ gate.qbi_deduction_usd | money(currency="USD") }}**, and your taxable income is **unchanged** by § 199A. Taxable income before the gate is {{ gate.taxable_income_before_qbi_usd | money(currency="USD") }} and after the gate is {{ gate.taxable_income_after_qbi_usd | money(currency="USD") }} — the gate subtracts nothing. No Form 8995 line is rendered: § 199A is explicitly not applicable (a cited status), never a zero deduction line.

Granting a 20 % deduction here would be an over-deduction the taxpayer is not entitled to. The engine refuses to do so.
